# Sequential edits with approval and review

## Before modifying any file

1. **State intent first** — Before applying edits, briefly say **which file** you will change, **what** you will change, and **why** (goal / constraint).
2. **Side effects** — Call out **potential side effects**: broken imports, tests, types, RSC vs `"use client"` boundaries, bundle size, a11y, behavior change elsewhere, need to run lint/build.
3. **Approval** — If the user’s request is **vague** (“clean this up”, “improve X”) or **multi-step**, **ask for explicit approval** on the proposed change to **that one file** before editing. If they **already** directed you to implement or fix something concrete (“add loading state to `Header.tsx`”), you may proceed **after** the pre-edit explanation in the same turn.

## During multi-file work

4. **One file per step** — Apply edits to **only one** file, then **stop**. Do not edit a second file in the same turn.
5. **After the edit** — Summarize what changed (and point to the path). Treat this as a checkpoint; **do not** start the next file until the user approves or asks to continue (e.g. “looks good”, “continue”, “next”).

## Exceptions (only when the user explicitly asks)

- “Do it all in one go” / “batch these files”
- Trivial paired edits they already approved as a single set (e.g. rename symbol across two agreed paths)

If unsure, default to **explain → (approval if needed) → one file → pause**.
